   <text facs="facs:RE-KbyMaryRobertsRinehart2">
      <body>
         <opener>
            <dateline>
               <date>January 22nd, 30</date>
            </dateline>
            <byline><name ref="pers:CGS1">Mr. C. Gardner Sullivan</name>
               <name ref="pers:WE1">Winnifred Reeve</name></byline>
            <byline>cc<name ref="pers:CL3">Mr. Carl Laemmle Jr</name>.</byline>
         </opener>
         <div>
            <p>RE: <q>K</q> by <name ref="pers:MRR1">Mary Roberts Rinehart</name></p>

            <p>Supplementing my previous memo, I have since read the continuity of this story, and
               which probably was used for the picture we produced.</p>

            <p>This contains considerable stuff that is not in the book. This is by way of comedy of
               an exaggerated nature but very popular a number of years ago. As, for instance, the
               old familiar stuff of the squabbling youths calling upon the heroine - - one losing
               the seat of his pants and unable to turn around, the other turning the lawn sprinkler
               on his rival, the other retaliating by hurling ripe tomatoes in his face. Also we
               have familiar trio of spinster gossips all nodding and shaking their heads in unison
               as they retail the tid-bits or big bits of scandal of the town, and quite a bit of
               footage is given to the old time picnic with the popular games etc.</p>

            <p>I dare say the above contributed in considerable measure to the success of the
               picture because I know that this sort of slap-stick comedy was much liked as that
               time, but it is very doubtful indeed, whether it would click today with a motion
               picture audience. </p>


         </div>
      </body>
